04864nam a22006495i 9780822373728DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20162016ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223737287 a10.1515/97808223737282doi  a(DE-B1597)551810  a(OCoLC)1170536290  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1075.5.A65bF74 2016 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a305.30917/492722300aFreedom without Permission :bBodies and Space in the Arab Revolutions /cZakia Salime, Frances S. Hasso. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b26 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. POLITICS IN THE DIGITAL BOUDOIR -- t2. GENDER AND THE FRACTURED MYTHSCAPES OF NATIONAL IDENTITY IN REVOLUTIONARY TUNISIA -- t3. MAKING INTIMATE "CIVILPOLITICS" IN SOUTHERN YEMEN -- t4. THE SECT-SEX-POLICE NEXUS AND POLITICS IN BAHRAIN'S PEARL REVOLUTION -- t5. "THE WOMEN ARE COMING" -- t6. CAUTIOUS ENACTMENTS -- t7. REVOLUTION UNDRESSED -- t8. INTIMATE POLITICS OF PROTEST -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the 2011 uprisings in North Africa reverberated across the Middle East, a diverse cross section of women and girls publicly disputed gender and sexual norms in novel, unauthorized, and often shocking ways. In a series of case studies ranging from Tunisia's 14 January Revolution to the Taksim Gezi Park protests in Istanbul, the contributors to Freedom without Permission reveal the centrality of the intersections between body, gender, sexuality, and space to these groundbreaking events. Essays include discussions of the blogs written by young women in Egypt, the Women2Drive campaign in Saudi Arabia, the reintegration of women into the public sphere in Yemen, the sexualization of female protesters encamped at Bahrain's Pearl Roundabout, and the embodied, performative, and artistic spaces of Morocco's 20 February Movement. Conceiving of revolution as affective, embodied, spatialized, and aesthetic forms of upheaval and transgression, the contributors show how women activists imagined, inhabited, and deployed new spatial arrangements that undermined the public-private divisions of spaces, bodies, and social relations, continuously transforming them through symbolic and embodied transgressions. Contributors. Lamia Benyoussef, Susanne Dahlgren, Karina Eileraas, Susana Galan, Banu Gökariksel, Frances S. Hasso, Sonali Pahwa, Zakia Salime  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aSex rolezArab countriesxHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aGökarıksel, Banu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasso, Frances S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasso, Frances S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEileraas, Karina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenyoussef, Lamia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalime, Zakia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPahwa, Sonali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalán, Susana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlgren, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalime, Zakia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373728zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyte